	<ul>
		<li><strong>Best choice:</strong> Vinyl (zero climbing, bending, or physical maintenance)</li>
		<li><strong>Runner-up:</strong> Aluminum (minimal maintenance, can hire for occasional cleaning)</li>
		<li><strong>Avoid:</strong> Any wood (too much physical labor required)</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>For Investment Properties:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Best choice:</strong> Vinyl (tenants won't maintain wood, vinyl stays nice)</li>
		<li><strong>Runner-up:</strong> Aluminum (durable, handles neglect better than wood)</li>
		<li><strong>Avoid:</strong> Wood (requires landlord to perform/pay for maintenance)</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>For Eco-Conscious Homeowners:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Best choice:</strong> Composite (recycled content, long lifespan)</li>
		<li><strong>Runner-up:</strong> Aluminum (100% recyclable, doesn't require chemical treatments)</li>
		<li><strong>Consider:</strong> Reclaimed wood if willing to maintain (but not low-maintenance)</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Installation Quality Impacts Maintenance</h2>

	<h3>Why Professional Installation Matters</h3>
	<p>Even low-maintenance materials require maintenance if poorly installed:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Proper post depth:</strong> Prevents leaning that requires costly correction</li>
		<li><strong>Correct spacing:</strong> Allows for expansion/contraction (especially composite)</li>
		<li><strong>Level installation:</strong> Prevents gates from sagging or panels from warping</li>
		<li><strong>Quality hardware:</strong> Stainless or coated hardware prevents rust issues</li>
		<li><strong>Drainage consideration:</strong> Posts installed with proper drainage prevent water damage</li>
		<li><strong>Code compliance:</strong> Avoid having to fix or rebuild fence to meet codes</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Questions to Ask Installers</h3>
	<p>Ensure your low-maintenance fence stays low-maintenance:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>What grade of vinyl/aluminum are you using? (Virgin vinyl, commercial-grade aluminum)</li>
		<li>What warranty do you provide on materials and labor?</li>
		<li>How deep will posts be set for this fence height?</li>
		<li>What type of hardware will you use? (Should be rust-proof)</li>
		<li>Do you account for expansion gaps in installation?</li>
		<li>How do you ensure fence stays level over time?</li>
		<li>What maintenance do you recommend for this specific fence?</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Common Low-Maintenance Fence Mistakes</h2>

	<h3>Errors That Create Maintenance Problems</h3>

	<p><strong>Mistake #1: Choosing Economy-Grade Materials</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Problem:</strong> Cheap vinyl cracks, fades; cheap aluminum dents easily</li>
		<li><strong>Result:</strong> "Low-maintenance" fence requires frequent repairs</li>
		<li><strong>Solution:</strong> Invest in mid-to-premium grade materials from reputable brands</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Mistake #2: Improper Installation Spacing</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Problem:</strong> No expansion gaps causes buckling in summer heat</li>
		<li><strong>Result:</strong> Panels warp, requiring maintenance and repair</li>
		<li><strong>Solution:</strong> Hire experienced installer who understands material properties</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Mistake #3: Ignoring Small Issues</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Problem:</strong> Small scratch or crack ignored becomes bigger problem</li>
		<li><strong>Result:</strong> Eventually requires panel replacement vs. simple touch-up</li>
		<li><strong>Solution:</strong> Address minor issues immediately (still minimal time)</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Mistake #4: Using Wrong Cleaning Products</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Problem:</strong> Harsh chemicals damage fence surface</li>
		<li><strong>Result:</strong> Discoloration, accelerated aging, voided warranties</li>
		<li><strong>Solution:</strong> Stick to mild soap and water, manufacturer-approved cleaners only</li>
	</ul>

